One Year of Manipur Violence

For almost a year now, Manipur has been torn apart by ethnic violence. Hundreds have died, and thousands have been displaced, with their future still uncertain. We, at The Quint, have tried to present every facet of the conflict in the northeastern state since the day it started – be it the plight of the victims or the state of the relief camps or clashes between the people and the security forces.

󠀠󠀠

Now, as Manipur votes for the two Lok Sabha seats starting 19 April, and with the one-year mark of the violence approaching right after on 3 May 2024, The Quint is going back to ground zero in pursuit of facts, untold stories, and the truth.

󠀠󠀠

Apart from the risks involved in reporting from a conflict-ridden area, such reports require both time and resources. You can support us by becoming a member – and help us in our endeavour.

Uncovering Hate: Investigations, Ground Reports & Deep Dives

In the last decade, India has seen a steep rise in incidents of hate crimes, discrimination, and communal violence. This doesn't mean mob lynchings alone but also targeted violence, arbitrary laws, and everyday forms of discrimination and hate. 

󠀠󠀠The Quint has consistently been the leading news organisation breaking stories on communal violence and hate crimes and carrying out in-depth investigations on communal issues – be it our documentary on the hijab ban in Karnataka and our investigations on the 2020 Northeast Delhi violence, the Uttar Pradesh Anti-Conversion laws and the violence being carried out by cow-protection vigilantes.

󠀠󠀠These investigations involve a lot of work and often come at great personal risk to our reporters who are on the ground. We need your support as we continue to bring out more such investigations and voices from the ground.

'Trapped' in Russia

"There is a lot of pressure here. They can take us back to the frontline anytime," said 20-year-old Harsh Kumar, one of the Indians 'trapped' in Russia who The Quint has been in touch with even as he awaits the help of the Indian government to be rescued from Russia. Like Kumar, dozens of Indians were allegedly duped by 'trafficking' agents on the pretext of job offers and sent to Russia – where they were forcefully recruited into the country's army and made to fight in the war against Ukraine. Not only from India but even from India's neighbour Nepal, at least 2,000 men have been recruited by the Russian Army. At least 33 have lost their lives in the conflict.

󠀠󠀠󠀠

Through our special reports and videos backed by foreign policy experts, we are bringing you untold stories of these men as they await their return home. Others, who were lucky enough to return, recount the horrors of serving in the Russian Army. Even as the ruling government spins a 'war rukwa di' campaign, what is the plight of the men 'trapped' in a foreign country? Help us continue our work by supporting us. Elections Fact-Check

As we gear up for the upcoming Lok Sabha elections, we are confronted with a formidable challenge: the rampant spread of misinformation. According to the World Economic Forum's 2024 Global Risk Report, India stands at the forefront of nations vulnerable to disinformation, posing a threat to the integrity of our democratic process.

󠀠󠀠

At The Quint, we believe that every citizen deserves access to accurate and verified information to make informed decisions at the ballot box. This election season, we are spending considerable resources towards empowering our audience with fact-checked news and real-time misinformation busts. But we cannot complete this without you.

󠀠󠀠

As a paying member, your support will enable us to invest in cutting-edge fact-checking technologies, engage expert journalists, and deliver comprehensive coverage that separates truth from falsehood. Together, we can combat disinformation, promote media literacy, and empower voters to make informed choices that shape the future of our nation.

󠀠󠀠

Your membership is not just an investment in quality journalism; it's a commitment to democracy.

2024 Lok Sabha Elections

2024 is poised to be a make-or-break year for democracy – and the Indian general elections is its biggest test. The upcoming polls are crucial for India – and the world over – as almost a billion people will cast their vote in seven phases. But what is the common voter thinking? What do they expect from their Member of Parliament? Will it be the local or national issues that will determine how they vote in the Lok Sabha elections?

The Quint has hit the ground running to bring you 360-degree coverage: our ground reports will take you face-to-face with the common voter and their issues. Our political analysis and explainers will help you understand the bigger picture of news events. Our opinion articles will offer you predictions and insights from experts.

All of this – and more – requires time and resources, and so we need your help. Support us this general election. Become a member and empower our reporters to do more and do better.

Broken Dreams: Inside the Homebuyers’ Nightmare

It is estimated that approximately INR 80,000 crore is currently stuck in construction-related disputes in various courts in the country. In Greater Noida alone, there are over 200 housing societies that are under various stages of development, most of which end up in disputes due to unfulfilled builder promises. In numerous instances, the cherished dream of home ownership remains an elusive reality for buyers, as possession continues to be an unfulfilled aspiration. The resolution sometimes takes years, leaving citizens in a state of financial and emotional distress.

The Quint's MyReport team aims to cover these conflicts, directly from the people afflicted. We will delve into first-hand stories of construction-related disputes, delayed possession, false assurances, and the emotional toll it brings on citizens. Your support will help us amplify the voices of homebuyers who have been stuck in housing dilemmas for years.

Electoral Bonds

In April 2018, an investigation by The Quint revealed that electoral bonds carried unique hidden alphanumeric numbers. Another investigation carried out in November 2019 found that the State Bank of India actually records these hidden numbers – making the government's claim of donor anonymity untrue. As the Supreme Court struck down electoral bonds as unconstitutional in a landmark judgment, it stood as a recognition of our award-winning investigation. 

󠀠󠀠

As the Election Commission of India reveals the SBI-provided data on electoral bonds, The Quint team is rigorously analysing the numbers and bringing you the bigger picture of the political donations made since 2019.

󠀠󠀠󠀠

This kind of rigorous journalism is possible because of readers like you. Support us to do more ground-breaking work. Become a member today.

'Suicide Mat Karna Bas': Inside The Kota Crisis

At least two lakh students from across India move to Rajasthan's Kota annually to prepare for entrance exams like the JEE and NEET. A small percentage of them make it to India's elite engineering and medical colleges, most of them settle for lesser-known colleges, some drop out altogether, but every year a significant number of students die by suicide – bringing to light the grim reality of India's coaching capital. So far, in 2023, at least 29 students have died by suicide – the highest number of student deaths in eight years. With this Special Project 'Suicide Mat Karna Bas', The Quint seeks to dive deep into the underlying factors contributing to the alarming rate of student suicides. This involves investigating the role of coaching centers, parental expectations, societal and financial pressures, and most importantly, the education system, in pushing students to the brink. Support us to bring to light the much-needed stories on mental health and academic stress.
